      "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
      "body" : "@Goh-shans - I didn&#39;t phrase that well (I&#39;ve updated it). In a string <i>literal</i>, a backslash is an escape character (<code>\\n</code> means newline, <code>\\t</code> means tab, etc.). So to put a backslash in the string, we have to escape it (with a backslash). So <code>&quot;[\\\\-.]&quot;</code> creates a regular expression using the string <code>[\\-.]</code>, which escapes the <code>-</code>. <b>But</b>, there&#39;s no need to do that when the <code>-</code> is the first character after the <code>[</code> anyway."
    } ],
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 52616,
      "reputation" : 1081540,
